Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:

> If we must wait_for_completion(), then we could still just hang forever it seems. Perhaps the 'struct ping_data' need to be allocated on the heap and kref'ed? Then whoever has an outstanding complete() can be guaranteed to have a valid pointer. If no one is wait_for_complete(), the data would get tossed out when that thread drops it's reference. I'll have to study the code more to see if this would work. This code is the only user of 'struct ping_data', so the change won't be huge.

The code won't hang forever.  After LNetMDUnlink() has been called we can be certain that complete() has been called, or that lnet_finalize is running on some other CPU and will call complete() every soon.  So there is risk of a wait_for_complete() call after an LNetMDUnlink() blocking indefinitely.

I thought more about how the code should look and I now think it would be clearer as:

if (wait_for_completion_interruptible_timeout() <= 0) {
      LNetMDUnlink();
      wait_for_completion();
}
